<subSubSection id="D6E265519278FFF3FF6FFF74FF611150" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFF74FF611150" blockId="14.[178,1085,219,270]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Etymology: The specific epithet (Latin, adjective) alludes to the conspicuously incrassate antennae.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D6E265519278FFF3FF6FFEB2FCF81427" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" type="description">
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFEB2FFF811D6" blockId="14.[178,1086,285,395]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
Description: Body length 4.0 mm; length of forebody 
<quantity id="59009B3F9278FFF3FCB8FEB2FDA6116E" box="[869,954,285,307]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: forebody black; abdomen yellowish-red, strongly contrasting with the forebody; legs dark-brown with paler tarsi; antennae with antennomeres I-III dark-brown and antennomeres IV-XI blackish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFE35FF76123D" blockId="14.[178,1085,410,608]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
Head (
<figureCitation id="06C32A5F9278FFF3FF2AFE35FF5F11EC" box="[247,323,410,433]" captionStart="Figs 22-27" captionStartId="13.[178,218,1371,1393]" captionTargetBox="[178,1071,395,1349]" captionTargetId="figure-104@13.[178,1077,395,1361]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 22-27: Orphnebius incrassatus nov.sp. (22-25) and O. formosanus nov.sp. (26-27): forebody (22); antenna (23); abdomen (24); spermatheca (25, 27); tergite VII (26). Scale bars: 22-24: 0.5 mm; 25-27: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413950/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) 1.25 times as broad as long; distinctly angled posteriorly in lateral view, i.e., dorsal surface meeting with posterior surface at a sharp angle; punctation of dorsal surface extremely fine and sparse. Eyes large and bulging, nearly reaching posterior margin in dorsal view. Antenna (
<figureCitation id="06C32A5F9278FFF3FDDCFE5DFC561255" box="[513,586,498,520]" captionStart="Figs 22-27" captionStartId="13.[178,218,1371,1393]" captionTargetBox="[178,1071,395,1349]" captionTargetId="figure-104@13.[178,1077,395,1361]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 22-27: Orphnebius incrassatus nov.sp. (22-25) and O. formosanus nov.sp. (26-27): forebody (22); antenna (23); abdomen (24); spermatheca (25, 27); tergite VII (26). Scale bars: 22-24: 0.5 mm; 25-27: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413950/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) 1.0 mm long, strongly incrassate; antennomeres IV moderately transverse; V-X strongly transverse, approximately twice as broad as long, of gradually increasing width; XI distinctly elongated, approximately as long as VIII-X combined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFDDFFC4712A7" blockId="14.[178,1085,623,762]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="06C32A5F9278FFF3FEF8FDC0FF6C12D8" box="[293,368,623,645]" captionStart="Figs 22-27" captionStartId="13.[178,218,1371,1393]" captionTargetBox="[178,1071,395,1349]" captionTargetId="figure-104@13.[178,1077,395,1361]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 22-27: Orphnebius incrassatus nov.sp. (22-25) and O. formosanus nov.sp. (26-27): forebody (22); antenna (23); abdomen (24); spermatheca (25, 27); tergite VII (26). Scale bars: 22-24: 0.5 mm; 25-27: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413950/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) strongly transverse, nearly 1.5 times as broad as long and 1.45 times as broad as head, broadest approximately in the middle; lateral margins strongly convex in dorsal view; posterior angles obsolete, broadly convex; disc nearly impunctate, only with scattered minute setiferous punctures; microsculpture absent; lateral margins each with few moderately long brownish setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFCA5FA221361" blockId="14.[178,1086,778,829]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="06C32A5F9278FFF3FEDCFCA5FF52137D" box="[257,334,778,800]" captionStart="Figs 22-27" captionStartId="13.[178,218,1371,1393]" captionTargetBox="[178,1071,395,1349]" captionTargetId="figure-104@13.[178,1077,395,1361]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 22-27: Orphnebius incrassatus nov.sp. (22-25) and O. formosanus nov.sp. (26-27): forebody (22); antenna (23); abdomen (24); spermatheca (25, 27); tergite VII (26). Scale bars: 22-24: 0.5 mm; 25-27: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413950/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) slightly shorter, and at posterior margin much broader than pronotum; punctation fine and sparse; pubescence whitish, sparse, and suberect. Hind wings present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFCE3FCC7138A" blockId="14.[178,1085,844,983]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation id="06C32A5F9278FFF3FEFBFCE3FF6F133F" box="[294,371,844,866]" captionStart="Figs 22-27" captionStartId="13.[178,218,1371,1393]" captionTargetBox="[178,1071,395,1349]" captionTargetId="figure-104@13.[178,1077,395,1361]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 22-27: Orphnebius incrassatus nov.sp. (22-25) and O. formosanus nov.sp. (26-27): forebody (22); antenna (23); abdomen (24); spermatheca (25, 27); tergite VII (26). Scale bars: 22-24: 0.5 mm; 25-27: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413950/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
) broad and wedge-shaped, widest at base; tergites III-VI with sharp and pronounced paratergites gradually decreasing in height; tergites III-VI impunctate except for some minute punctures at posterior margins; tergite VII with rather coarse, oblong, and moderately dense non-setiferous punctures in posterior two-thirds; posterior margin of tergite VII with pronounced palisade fringe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFC48FF2613A0" blockId="14.[178,314,999,1021]" box="[178,314,999,1021]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">♂: unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFBBDFCF81427" blockId="14.[178,1085,1036,1146]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
<specimenCount id="88FEFD539278FFF3FF6FFBBDFEDB147A" box="[178,199,1042,1063]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: tergite VIII posteriorly approximately 20 fine dark setae posteriorly, posterior margin broadly and strongly convex; sternite VIII with broadly and strongly convex posterior margin; sclerites of segments IX and X modified, with dense and moderately long pubescence; spermatheca (
<figureCitation id="06C32A5F9278FFF3FE1DFBCBFC151427" box="[448,521,1124,1146]" captionStart="Figs 22-27" captionStartId="13.[178,218,1371,1393]" captionTargetBox="[178,1071,395,1349]" captionTargetId="figure-104@13.[178,1077,395,1361]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 22-27: Orphnebius incrassatus nov.sp. (22-25) and O. formosanus nov.sp. (26-27): forebody (22); antenna (23); abdomen (24); spermatheca (25, 27); tergite VII (26). Scale bars: 22-24: 0.5 mm; 25-27: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5413950" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5413950/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
) of distinctive shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D6E265519278FFF3FF6FFB26FF5315B4" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFB26FA3D14E1" blockId="14.[178,1085,1161,1212]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Comment: This species is described exclusively based on a female because the external characters and the shape of the spermatheca are most likely highly distinctive.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFB63FF5315B4" blockId="14.[178,1085,1228,1513]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
Comparative notes: Based on the modified abdominal segments IX-X, 
<taxonomicName id="59F84D599278FFF3FBF9FB63FF3914A2" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orphnebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incrassatus">
<emphasis id="AC8CEAC89278FFF3FBF9FB63FF3914A2" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">O. incrassatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="59F84D599278FFF3FE0BFB46FC5B14A3" authorityName="EPPELSHEIM" authorityYear="1895" box="[470,583,1257,1278]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orphnebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hauseri">
<emphasis id="AC8CEAC89278FFF3FE0BFB46FC5B14A3" box="[470,583,1257,1278]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">O. hauseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group sensu lato. It is distinguished from the species of the 
<taxonomicName id="59F84D599278FFF3FE9EFAA8FFB31546" authorityName="EPPELSHEIM" authorityYear="1895" box="[323,431,1286,1308]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orphnebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hauseri">
<emphasis id="AC8CEAC89278FFF3FE9EFAA8FFB31546" box="[323,431,1286,1308]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">O. hauseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group sensu strictu by the strongly transverse pronotum and the shape of the spermatheca. As can be inferred from external characters (head posteriorly angled in lateral view; pronotum strongly transverse and with obsolete posterior angles; chaetotaxy of the abdomen) and the shape of the spermatheca, 
<taxonomicName id="59F84D599278FFF3FC8FFAF1FDFB1529" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2015" box="[850,999,1374,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orphnebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incrassatus">
<emphasis id="AC8CEAC89278FFF3FC8FFAF1FDFB1529" box="[850,999,1374,1396]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">O. incrassatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most closely allied to the geographically close 
<taxonomicName id="59F84D599278FFF3FD86FAD3FD4115CC" authority="ASSING, 2009" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2009" box="[603,861,1403,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orphnebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncus">
<emphasis id="AC8CEAC89278FFF3FD86FAD3FCDB15CC" box="[603,711,1404,1425]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">O. truncus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="FA694B2B9278FFF3FD13FAD4FD4115CC" author="ASSING V" box="[718,861,1403,1425]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" pagination="201 - 226" refId="ref13153" refString="ASSING V. (2009): New species and additional records of Lomechusini from the Palaearctic region (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae). - Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde Serie A, Neue Serie 2: 201 - 226." type="journal article" year="2009">ASSING, 2009</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs particularly by the conspicuously incrassate antennae, the darker coloration of the legs and the antennae, and by the shape of the spermatheca. For illustrations of 
<taxonomicName id="59F84D599278FFF3FC76FA19FA0A1591" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2009" box="[939,1046,1462,1484]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orphnebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncus">
<emphasis id="AC8CEAC89278FFF3FC76FA19FA0A1591" box="[939,1046,1462,1484]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">O. truncus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation id="FA694B2B9278FFF3FF6FFA7CFF5715B4" author="ASSING V" box="[178,331,1491,1513]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" pagination="201 - 226" refId="ref13153" refString="ASSING V. (2009): New species and additional records of Lomechusini from the Palaearctic region (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae). - Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde Serie A, Neue Serie 2: 201 - 226." type="journal article" year="2009">ASSING (2009)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D6E265519278FFF3FF6FFA57FCB81614" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9E4736DA9278FFF3FF6FFA57FCB81614" blockId="14.[178,1085,1528,1609]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">
Distribution and natural history: The type locality is situated in the Gaoligong Shan in western 
<collectingRegion id="5C3CF8389278FFF3FDD8F9B9FC441676" box="[517,600,1558,1579]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
. The 
<typeStatus id="414388789278FFF3FD4AF9B9FCEC1671" box="[663,752,1558,1580]" pageId="14" pageNumber="115">holotype</typeStatus>
was sifted from leaf litter in a degraded primary forest at an altitude of 
<quantity id="59009B3F9278FFF3FD8DF99CFC831614" box="[592,671,1587,1609]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" pageId="14" pageNumber="115" unit="m" value="2150.0">2150 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
